WEBVTT



00:00:00.768 --> 00:00:04.576
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:00:04.384 --> 00:00:09.792
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization.

00:00:09.600 --> 00:00:15.040
Using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent,

00:00:14.752 --> 00:00:18.752
and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:00:18.848 --> 00:00:27.040
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:00:27.008 --> 00:00:36.448
Today, we invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:00:37.728 --> 00:00:46.208
Peace be with you. Friends, we have a great privilege this year because the Feast of the Exaltation of the Holy Cross, September the 14th, falls on a Sunday.

00:00:45.824 --> 00:00:48.832
So we have a chance to reflect a bit more deeply on this topic.

00:00:49.120 --> 00:00:50.720
Marvelous. Marvelous.

00:00:50.464 --> 00:00:54.144
Frankly, disconcerting, odd feast.

00:00:53.920 --> 00:00:55.840
Now, how come I say it that way?

00:00:56.288 --> 00:01:04.608
Well, let me take you back to this very morning. So I always wake up early. I do my holy hour first thing. And I go to my chapel. In my chapel, I'm

00:01:04.864 --> 00:01:09.056
I have a chair and I'm facing the altar in the tabernacle for the holy hour.

00:01:08.608 --> 00:01:11.456
And right in the front of the altar, I have this

00:01:11.264 --> 00:01:15.456
uh Golden Cross was given me by a friend many years ago and

00:01:15.040 --> 00:01:19.680
And it's beautiful. It's kind of the gothic design, very elaborate.

00:01:19.648 --> 00:01:25.984
And it's very prayerful. The minute I see that cross, I kind of move into a prayerful frame of mind.

00:01:26.176 --> 00:01:27.136
But,

00:01:26.944 --> 00:01:28.192
Um.

00:01:28.064 --> 00:01:30.080
So if you were to strip away something

00:01:30.144 --> 00:01:36.256
The decoration, the gold and the siligree and the gothic, you know, trimmings and all that.

00:01:36.096 --> 00:01:39.872
And you brought it back to what it essentially is.

00:01:39.744 --> 00:01:41.408
A Roman Cross.

00:01:41.984 --> 00:01:43.264
You'd see it.

00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:45.536
Indeed, it's something terrible.

00:01:45.888 --> 00:01:49.184
And something brutal and awful.

00:01:49.760 --> 00:01:53.824
And all the poetry of this feast is summed up in the fact that

00:01:54.240 --> 00:01:58.176
I've got on that altar that awful thing.

00:01:58.016 --> 00:01:59.968
That awful thing

00:02:00.128 --> 00:02:04.896
in gold and decoration and and filigree I'm

00:02:05.152 --> 00:02:08.000
Weirdly exalting

00:02:08.288 --> 00:02:10.816
This horrific thing.

00:02:11.296 --> 00:02:21.344
You know, again, if someone came back from the ancient world and they were brought into that chapel and said, here's a place where this man is praying, it's a religious room, and he'd look at that.

00:02:20.864 --> 00:02:23.232
And that decoration is saying, well, wait a minute.

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:26.080
That's a cross.

00:02:26.272 --> 00:02:27.936
That's where people are.

00:02:27.872 --> 00:02:30.592
brutally put to death.

00:02:30.848 --> 00:02:31.840
Uh-huh.

00:02:32.128 --> 00:02:34.432
And he's praying?

00:02:34.272 --> 00:02:43.136
And in front of Vanity's, cover it in gold. It's like, you know, if you had a hangman's scaffold and noose, right?

00:02:43.264 --> 00:02:46.688
And it's all covered in gold and flowers around it.

00:02:46.880 --> 00:02:48.768
Like you had an electric chair,

00:02:48.800 --> 00:02:52.544
But gold and with Gothic designs and...

00:02:52.832 --> 00:02:55.232
People will say, well, what's the matter with you?

00:02:55.936 --> 00:02:57.440
That's all the

00:02:57.376 --> 00:03:01.888
100% weird poetry, everybody, in this feast. You know what came to mind as I thought more about that?

00:03:02.048 --> 00:03:03.296
It was a great experience.

00:03:02.976 --> 00:03:10.944
show on hbo about twenty years ago called the rome series i think was only two seasons but it was so well done and it.

00:03:10.944 --> 00:03:18.944
evoked that time of Julius Caesar and that whole period of Mark Antony, that pivotal moment in Roman history.

00:03:18.720 --> 00:03:21.760
Well, one of the, maybe the first episode.

00:03:21.760 --> 00:03:25.792
Yeah. You're with Cesar up in Gaul, and he's got his army with him.

00:03:25.632 --> 00:03:33.696
And the standard has been stolen by these local soldiers, local barbarians, as the Romans saw them.

00:03:34.016 --> 00:03:44.064
And the commander calls in the main character, Varinus, this Roman soldier, and he says, "Varinus, the standard's been captured and Caesar won."

00:03:43.584 --> 00:03:44.832
These are Watts of Back.

00:03:44.864 --> 00:03:46.144
Yes, sir.

00:03:45.984 --> 00:03:52.960
And he says, well, now what do you propose? How are you going to do it? And he said, I'll go to the neighboring villages and I'll crucify the men until I find out

00:03:52.736 --> 00:03:54.784
And the commander said, okay, good.

00:03:54.496 --> 00:04:02.208
And then the next scene is this man being nailed to a cross and screaming in pain and

00:04:02.112 --> 00:04:08.512
And he reveals where the standards are. And then the next scene is Varidis is coming back with the standard.

00:04:08.512 --> 00:04:10.912
Now, I bring that up because

00:04:11.328 --> 00:04:13.472
I think that captures beautifully.

00:04:13.600 --> 00:04:16.480
The attitude of ancient Rome.

00:04:17.024 --> 00:04:19.328
You know, when Cesar went into Gaul,

00:04:19.680 --> 00:04:29.728
If they estimate there are about 3 million people in Gaul, he killed a million. That's a conservative estimate. There was a genocide of a million people that Caesar killed. He enslaved another

00:04:29.248 --> 00:04:39.296
Another million, the remaining million are the foundation for the Roman province of Gaul, which then became, in time, modern-day France. But when Caesar went in, they

00:04:38.816 --> 00:04:39.456
And, again,

00:04:39.648 --> 00:04:45.984
And he brutalized the people. And yes, he would crucify people right and left. Right.

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:52.480
It was a sign of Roman power. That's how Rome exerted its kind of

00:04:52.448 --> 00:04:54.720
ruthless control

00:04:54.400 --> 00:04:55.680
over people.

00:04:55.776 --> 00:04:59.840
It was meant to terrify. It was state-sponsored.

00:04:59.808 --> 00:05:01.056
Terrorism. Terrorism.

00:05:01.312 --> 00:05:03.680
It was the way Rome controlled.

00:05:03.744 --> 00:05:05.952
And here's the thing I find really interesting.

00:05:06.208 --> 00:05:11.968
Yes, indeed, there were people in Rome that thought Caesar was ambitious, and they didn't like that.

00:05:11.904 --> 00:05:16.352
They were very sensitive to people, you know, seizing power illegitimately.

00:05:15.968 --> 00:05:26.016
So the crossing of the Rubicon and all of that, they were very aware of that. But listen, nobody complained that Caesar killed a million people.

00:05:25.536 --> 00:05:35.584
That didn't bother them at all. In fact, they thought that was a side of what a great commander he was, what a great general he was. Nobody in Rome would have said, oh, did you hear he crucified?

00:05:35.104 --> 00:05:38.816
Crucified? He crucified all these people, right?

00:05:39.072 --> 00:05:41.664
That didn't bother them at all.

00:05:41.408 --> 00:05:44.768
Yeah. Like the commander in that series. Well, what's your plan? Well...

00:05:44.448 --> 00:05:48.352
I'll crucify him until I find out where the sanders are. Okay, good. Off you go.

00:05:49.344 --> 00:05:52.384
But that's what the cross is.

00:05:52.416 --> 00:05:53.600
Mint.

00:05:55.200 --> 00:05:58.144
A horrific, terrifying

00:05:58.752 --> 00:06:02.304
symbol of of tyrannical power.

00:06:02.944 --> 00:06:08.768
And so, if you were talking in the ancient world about the exaltation of the cross,

00:06:09.152 --> 00:06:11.424
they would think you were out of your mind.

00:06:11.584 --> 00:06:20.032
Yeah. I'm afraid of the cross. Yeah, I get that. It's a sign of Rome's control. Yeah, I get that.

00:06:20.192 --> 00:06:23.616
But I'm going to exalt it and I'm going to put gold on it.

00:06:23.488 --> 00:06:26.528
I'm going to use it as a focus for my prayer.

00:06:27.008 --> 00:06:28.000
Okay.

00:06:28.032 --> 00:06:29.792
With all that in mind,

00:06:30.336 --> 00:06:35.552
We have to remember now how strange was the emergence of Christianity.

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:39.168
The first Christians come forth.

00:06:39.232 --> 00:06:43.456
not denying the cross of Jesus. That's how Jesus died.

00:06:43.424 --> 00:06:46.176
He died on one of those Roman crosses.

00:06:46.496 --> 00:06:49.760
nailed to it mercilessly, left

00:06:49.568 --> 00:06:51.104
To the elements.

00:06:50.976 --> 00:06:56.544
To to writhe in pain, slowly bleeding to death and asphyxiating.

00:06:57.280 --> 00:07:03.424
In most Roman crucifixions, people were just left on the cross for the birds of the air and the animals.

00:07:03.360 --> 00:07:06.944
In Jesus' case, because the Sabbath was coming, they took him down.

00:07:06.624 --> 00:07:09.824
But that's how that's how he died.

00:07:09.792 --> 00:07:13.056
As one more victim of this horrific

00:07:13.184 --> 00:07:14.176
Tyranny,

00:07:15.584 --> 00:07:17.088
The first Christians

00:07:16.928 --> 00:07:18.432
They don't hide it.

00:07:18.112 --> 00:07:24.032
And they don't pretend, oh, he died some other way or somehow he avoided it. No, no.

00:07:23.712 --> 00:07:26.240
Paul says, I know one thing, right?

00:07:26.176 --> 00:07:28.096
Christ in him crucified.

00:07:28.224 --> 00:07:33.568
They preach a mashiach of Israel, a messiah, an anointed.

00:07:33.504 --> 00:07:37.248
The anointed was to be the king of Israel. Yes, indeed.

00:07:37.216 --> 00:07:45.792
And the clearest indication possible that you were not the Mashiach would have been your death at the hands of Israel's enemies.

00:07:45.984 --> 00:07:48.288
That was the best sign possible.

00:07:49.024 --> 00:07:51.456
But yet they announce him

00:07:51.552 --> 00:07:54.624
They announced the crucified Lord.

00:07:56.160 --> 00:07:58.720
How do we begin to explain this?

00:07:59.104 --> 00:08:02.496
It seems to me, everybody, and I'm speaking here, not enough.

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:06.592
simply as a theologian. I'm trying to speak just as an historian.

00:08:07.168 --> 00:08:09.856
How do you explain the emergence of Christianity?

00:08:11.072 --> 00:08:14.816
Apart from the resurrection of Jesus from the dead.

00:08:16.128 --> 00:08:19.328
Apart from an act that was so staggering

00:08:19.680 --> 00:08:23.008
That it conquered and mocked.

00:08:23.104 --> 00:08:26.400
Even this most brutal sign

00:08:26.240 --> 00:08:27.136
of

00:08:27.104 --> 00:08:31.136
Tyranny and power and cruelty and violence

00:08:32.992 --> 00:08:34.112
That's how.

00:08:34.304 --> 00:08:37.728
Again, I'm speaking as an historian.

00:08:37.568 --> 00:08:40.512
How do you explain the emergence

00:08:40.704 --> 00:08:42.464
of Christianity. And these

00:08:42.208 --> 00:08:45.216
These men going to their deaths proclaiming.

00:08:45.568 --> 00:08:47.104
Jesus is Lord.

00:08:48.352 --> 00:08:51.328
It's only the resurrection of Jesus from the dead.

00:08:51.872 --> 00:08:52.736
Now,

00:08:53.248 --> 00:08:58.272
That as we look upon the exalted cross, the

00:08:58.848 --> 00:09:02.144
As we look at it in light of the resurrection, what do we see?

00:09:02.688 --> 00:09:04.256
Well, we see

00:09:04.512 --> 00:09:06.624
A world turned.

00:09:06.528 --> 00:09:09.056
Absolutely upside down

00:09:09.216 --> 00:09:14.368
Now, let me share something with you. And I get this from Tom Holland, the historian.

00:09:14.592 --> 00:09:18.592
So I mentioned how Caesar conquers Gaul and kills a million people.

00:09:18.656 --> 00:09:27.552
His ambition bothered Romans, but the genocide of a million people, that didn't bother the Romans. His crucifixion, that didn't bother the Romans.

00:09:27.872 --> 00:09:31.136
Why everybody? Why today?

00:09:31.040 --> 00:09:36.704
If someone commits a genocide on that scale, we would say he's a moral

00:09:36.544 --> 00:09:38.016
Reprobate.

00:09:37.824 --> 00:09:47.872
Yeah. We say he's a monster. Indeed, we have examples, sadly, in the recent times of people doing just that. And we say with complete confidence what horrible people there are.

00:09:47.392 --> 00:09:50.176
People there, why do we say that?

00:09:50.496 --> 00:09:55.264
Not because somehow, oh yeah, everyone's always said that. They didn't.

00:09:55.008 --> 00:09:56.992
They didn't always say it.

00:09:57.920 --> 00:09:59.744
What happened was,

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:02.176
The resurrection of Jesus from the dead.

00:10:02.912 --> 00:10:04.448
Which showed?

00:10:04.992 --> 00:10:07.584
God is not on the side

00:10:07.744 --> 00:10:09.344
of the tyrants.

00:10:09.824 --> 00:10:11.392
And the murderers.

00:10:11.360 --> 00:10:14.400
And those who assert themselves through violence.

00:10:14.464 --> 00:10:16.768
But rather, God is on the side.

00:10:17.056 --> 00:10:18.400
Of the victim.

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:19.584
Of these things

00:10:20.640 --> 00:10:28.800
Look now at this second reading for today, which is from one of the great texts in the New Testament. It's from the second chapter of Paul to the Philippians.

00:10:29.280 --> 00:10:30.208
Listen.

00:10:30.240 --> 00:10:31.776
Christ Jesus

00:10:31.712 --> 00:10:34.144
you know, Jesus Christos there.

00:10:34.016 --> 00:10:37.280
Yeshua Mashiach, Jesus the Messiah.

00:10:37.184 --> 00:10:41.280
See, and all that irony is there now that Jesus died.

00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:43.488
The crucified one is the Mashiach.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.944
Christ Jesus, though he was in the form of God,

00:10:46.944 --> 00:10:51.360
It did not deem equality with God something to be grasped.

00:10:51.808 --> 00:10:56.512
Mind you, who did deem equality with God something to be grasped?

00:10:56.896 --> 00:10:58.176
Edom,

00:10:58.144 --> 00:11:00.320
That's the original sin.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:07.136
Yeah. Eating from the tree of the knowledge of good and evil. Oh, the devil says, you know, he knows if you eat that, you'll be like him. Yeah.

00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:12.288
knowing good and evil. Adam, the nature of sin, is to grasp

00:11:12.064 --> 00:11:21.120
At divinity. Well, Jesus, who really is God, doesn't deem equality with God a thing to be grasped. Rather, what? Divinity.

00:11:21.056 --> 00:11:23.072
He emptied himself.

00:11:23.072 --> 00:11:25.568
And took the form of a slave.

00:11:25.568 --> 00:11:29.600
Roman society? A slave? Nobody.

00:11:29.376 --> 00:11:30.720
At the bottom.

00:11:30.528 --> 00:11:38.496
Slave, if you kill the slave, nobody would care. That's your prerogative. You abuse a slave in every possible way. That's your prerogative.

00:11:38.528 --> 00:11:39.712
But see.

00:11:40.064 --> 00:11:41.344
God

00:11:41.280 --> 00:11:43.136
It takes the form of a slave.

00:11:43.744 --> 00:11:45.536
Coming in human likeness.

00:11:45.440 --> 00:11:46.944
Humble himself

00:11:46.752 --> 00:11:47.712
Listen now.

00:11:47.616 --> 00:11:50.464
1. Becoming obedient to death.

00:11:50.784 --> 00:11:53.984
Even death on a cross.

00:11:54.880 --> 00:12:04.128
Everything I've said about the cross now is contained in that little line. And St. Paul, who grew up in that Roman culture, he knew it very well.

00:12:06.400 --> 00:12:11.392
Sin is the human tendency to exalt itself, right?

00:12:11.936 --> 00:12:13.568
"'How's it answered?' said the man.

00:12:13.760 --> 00:12:17.472
By a divine condescension that goes down

00:12:19.072 --> 00:12:22.112
We we aggrandize ourselves

00:12:21.920 --> 00:12:22.944
God,

00:12:22.848 --> 00:12:24.576
Empties himself.

00:12:24.928 --> 00:12:29.792
We always try to get to the top of society, whatever that means.

00:12:30.112 --> 00:12:31.232
God,

00:12:31.040 --> 00:12:32.864
Willingly goes

00:12:33.056 --> 00:12:34.752
All the way down,

00:12:35.040 --> 00:12:36.448
Into death

00:12:36.320 --> 00:12:38.464
Even death on a cross.

00:12:38.656 --> 00:12:39.808
Now listen.

00:12:40.032 --> 00:12:42.176
Because of this, God

00:12:42.272 --> 00:12:43.968
Exalted him.

00:12:44.064 --> 00:12:49.440
and bestowed upon him the name above every other name. Here's the resurrection of Jesus from the dead.

00:12:49.760 --> 00:12:52.640
But let me just stay for a minute with the dissent.

00:12:53.952 --> 00:12:57.952
If if you want to really help a child.

00:12:57.856 --> 00:12:59.520
Who's misbehaving?

00:12:59.360 --> 00:13:05.408
I mean, you can say from a distance, you know, you're wrong and you can name the problem and you can send a punishment, right?

00:13:05.632 --> 00:13:07.296
Is that going to help the kid?

00:13:08.064 --> 00:13:11.872
What's going to help the kid is if you you crouch down

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.704
And and try to enter as much as possible into that child's world.

00:13:16.448 --> 00:13:17.728
And to

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:21.568
We make the child, as it were, from the inside.

00:13:21.792 --> 00:13:25.376
You've entered into his world. You've gone down into it.

00:13:25.536 --> 00:13:28.384
If you want to fix a car,

00:13:28.032 --> 00:13:38.080
You're not going to say, hey, that car isn't working. Well, I can do that from the outside. You want to fix it? You've got to go all the way down into the car, open the hood, go under the car.

00:13:37.600 --> 00:13:42.208
Get your hands into it. Only then will you be able to fix it.

00:13:42.144 --> 00:13:48.032
So you want to fix the human race, which is dysfunctional.

00:13:48.064 --> 00:13:54.592
And which is beautifully expressed in the cross in all of its cruelty and violence.

00:13:54.688 --> 00:13:58.208
Right. If you want to fix that, where do you have to go?

00:13:58.752 --> 00:14:01.696
You have to go all the way

00:14:01.600 --> 00:14:02.528
Down.

00:14:02.816 --> 00:14:05.632
He accepted even death.

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:07.648
Death on a cross.

00:14:07.872 --> 00:14:11.776
Can you see the cross, everybody, as God's descent?

00:14:11.872 --> 00:14:17.056
Into the very thing that is most wrong with us.

00:14:17.152 --> 00:14:22.176
It's his descent into our cruelty and hatred and violence.

00:14:22.528 --> 00:14:27.424
And then it's a remaking of it from the inside.

00:14:27.904 --> 00:14:31.456
Jesus' word of forgiveness from the cross.

00:14:32.096 --> 00:14:34.144
It means that God's love is

00:14:33.952 --> 00:14:35.744
Is more powerful

00:14:35.584 --> 00:14:37.984
Than anything that's in the world.

00:14:38.400 --> 00:14:39.680
And therefore,

00:14:39.488 --> 00:14:43.136
That cross becomes the beginning of our salvation.

00:14:43.296 --> 00:14:45.376
That cross, which was the

00:14:45.216 --> 00:14:49.184
low point in Roman society is now

00:14:49.152 --> 00:14:52.064
Exalted. Exalted. There's our feast.

00:14:52.032 --> 00:15:02.080
the exaltation of the Holy Cross. Now we do indeed put gold on it. We put filigree around it. We do indeed put it in chapels and make it a

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:10.240
and make it a focus of prayer. Because on that cross, God went all the way down to fix from the inside things.

00:15:10.144 --> 00:15:12.448
All that's dysfunctional in us.

00:15:13.344 --> 00:15:18.432
And that's why we could say with Paul, I know one thing.

00:15:18.912 --> 00:15:20.928
Christ in Him crucified.

00:15:21.568 --> 00:15:22.816
And God bless you.

00:15:26.752 --> 00:15:30.976
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:36.320
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire dot Org.
